caption: Outdoor dining is lovely on a nice day (individual heaters available too). So glad we got to try this place, had this place bookmarked for years but never had the chance.  Shared the patacones with shrimp, avocado and this pepper/tomato sauce or salsa spread - great appetizer, thought it was kind of small, two plantain rounds with maybe 4 shrimp for $14. We tried the grilled cheese with sweet plantains and the pernil entree. Definitely liked the grilled cheese better - what's better than perfectly ripe maduros, salty melty cheese and super buttery perfectly toasted bread ?!? Pernil wasnt bad but was a little disappointed by black beans, maybe I have high standards for rice and beans. Liked that it came with both maduro and a little yucca thrown in for good measure. Ended up being $30 per person including tip, which is fair for the location. Quick, efficient and friendly service.
Yummy

Don't get me wrong, the pressed cuban sandwich is good. The green sauce was fantastic. However, at $17.50 after tax I can't recommend this sandwich. Save your money and eat somewhere else. There's great food nearby.  For what it's worth, you can get a better sandwich at half the price 3 blocks south at the bodega on Bedford/Gates.

This place was great, but when they opened up the bakery next door... mamma mia. All I do these days is eat guava pastries. One two three, right into the old tum. Sorry to my pants, I cannot fit anymore.

Nestled in the heart of Brooklyn, Pilar is a cozy cuban place reminisce of havana late nights. Menu is a great mix of cubano/hispanic classics with some new twist like their Pilar Grilled Cheese which I had and was amazing. Great music with service to boot. Would go back.

We’re so glad we found this place.

The pork was smothered with onions on top which ended up steaming the pork on the bottom. Although the pork was flavorful it didn't have the mouth feel as a traditional Cuban prepared pernil. My husband and I paid $70 for brunch. I have eaten these dishes in many places not so trendy and they've been as good or better and I paid half that price.

And you should definitely get the fresh plantain chips as the side, the garlic dipping sauce is a perfect compliment to the crunch. Full bar if you need libations. Warm glowing restaurant in a lovely part of Brooklyn with a nice upbeat atmosphere playing perfect 80s Classics which I just loved.. Fast service but the manageress lacked a little warmth in seating us, and the other waitress was nice but seemed a tad inexperienced as she took our food order and was about to leave before I asked if we could have some drinks. The drinks menu has a good selection of cocktails and craft beers. The food was largely a miss unfortunately and far from special. None of our group were that impressed and I tried a bit of everyone’s and no flavours sang. We’ve all had Cuban food vastly superior to this on numerous occasions. Now unfortunately I have to give a huge red flag mention to the Cuban burger which was a ghastly creation. It left a strong unpalatable bitter taste due to the chopped chorizo mixed into the patty. Everything about it lacked any juiciness or decent flavour. The bun was hard and fairly dry. Burgers are my favourite food and this may have been the worst I’ve ever had. In fact on reflection, it was. I regretted eating the half I had and wish I could erase the taste from my memory. Prices slightly too high I feel too, expect to pay around $15 - $22 for a main dish. So 3 stars Overall but mainly for the environment, food very disappointing.

I'm a fan. Even though this place is a bit overpriced. Even though some of the food options lack flavor. I'm still a fan. What can I say? I guess if you're the type of person that sticks with the couple of food options you know are good at a place, then Pilar might be for you.  When I come, I almost always get the arroz con pollo. For $17, you get a flavorful rice dish filled with chicken and plantains. ALWAYS get the house made hot sauce! It's a game changer. I've ventured into the drinks and apps too; the staples for me are the onion croquette and mojito (which are both $4-$6 during HH).  Unfortunately, whenever I venture away from my perfect meal here to try something new, I'm usually disappointed. Which leaves me feeling *facepalm emoji* for getting something blander yet miraculously more expensive.  I'd recommend coming here at HH. Figure out what it is you like, and get it every time. You won't be disappointed.

Great place for (more or less) authentic cuban food and drinks. I went here twice, once alone for dinner and another time for breakfast/lunch with friends, both times having a good experience. I can also recommend their Old Fashioned made with Rum. Very good cocktail.

I couldn't wait to review this place because I stumbled upon it during a long weekend trip to Brooklyn and Maaaaan let me tell you...THIS PLACE IS ABSOLUTELY OUTSTANDING!! First day was for brunch and I was beyond excited to see a legit Arroz con Pollo on the menu! Amazing!! Second day I couldn't get back there fast enough. Had a Cuban Irish Breakfast that had me all emotional. Amazing! Let's not forget the drinks, service and casual comfortable feel. Excellent,  Excellent Excellent.  Everything blended well together.  Nothing overbearing, nothing bland. Everything was Just right!! I would stand by my statement that this place IS DEFINITELY one of the best Cuban Cuisine restaurants in the country!! I'm hard to impress over food, but this place deserves your business.  Your belly will thank you!! Well done Pilar!!!👏👏👏
